Understanding and Exploring Customer Insurtance Data

Context:

Leveraging customer information is of atmost importance for the Helathcare Insurance Sector. Understanding and Exploring the insurance data will provide valuable insights for the Helathcare Insurance business.

  1. It will help in price optimization to provide better service at cost effective premiums thereby maximizing profits and maintaining customer loyalty.
  2. It will also help with customer segmentation so that insurance products can be better positioned for specific customer expectations.
  3. It will help in risk assessment to assess the individual and group risks so that appropriate costs can be factored while pricing the insurance products.

About the Data:

The data in context is about Customer Insurance information. The information contains data such as:

  1. Age: age of primary beneficiary
  2. Sex: insurance contractor gender, female, male
  3. BMI: Body mass index, providing an understanding of body, weights that are relatively high or low relative to height, objective index of body weight (kg / m ^ 2) using the ratio of height to weight, ideally 18.5 to 24.9
  4. Children: Number of children covered by health insurance / Number of dependents
  5. Smoker: Smoking
  6. Region: the beneficiary's residential area in the US, northeast, southeast, southwest, northwest.
  7. Charges: Individual medical costs billed by health insurance.

Objective

Deep dive into the data for valuable insights and conduct:

  1. Statistical analysis
  2. Exploratory Data Analysis
  3. Hypothesis Testing

3f. EDA - MEASURE OF SKEWNESS OF BMI, AGE, AND CHARGES COLUMNS
Skewness is a measure of assymetry of a distribution.

  1. When a distribution is asymmetrical the tail of the distribution is skewed to one side-to the right or to the left.

  2. When the value of the skewness is negative, the tail of the distribution is longer towards the left hand side of the curve.

  3. When the value of the skewness is positive, the tail of the distribution is longer towards the right hand side of the curve. </ol> We will use the skew() in the Dataframe class to determine the skewness for BMI, AGE & CHARGES

    Skewness for Age, BMI and Charges

In [15]:

charges     1.515880

Hence,

  1. 'age' is skewed to the right (positively skewed).
  2. 'bmi' is skewed to the right (positively skewed).
  3. 'charges' is skewed to the right (positively skewed).

Alternatively, the above can also be deduced by computing the statistical 5-number summary for the measures as follows.

The 5-Number Summary: Compute the 5-Number Summary:

  1. Minimum.
  2. Q1.
  3. Median(Q2).
  4. Q3.
  5. Max

The relationship between the 5-number summaries can also determine the distribution shape.

    For Age:

  • Median - Min = 39.00 - 18.00 = 21.00
  • Max - Median = 64.00 - 39.00 = 25.00
  • Q1 - Min = 27.00 - 18.00 = 9.00
  • Max - Q3 = 64.00 - 51.00 = 13.00
  • Median - Q1 = 39.00 - 27.00 = 9.00
  • Q3 - Median = 51.00 - 39.00 = 18.00

    • Since,

    Max-Median > Median-Min
    and

    Max-Q3 > Q1-Min
    and

    Q3-Median > Median-Q1
    the 'Age' distribution curve is Right-Skewed.

    Likewise the relationship for the 5-Number summaries of 'BMI' and 'Charges' can also be computed to determine that they are Right-Skewed.

    2. Z-score method Z-score indicates the number of standard deviations from the mean and when the threshold score is greater than 3 or less than -3, it is considered an outllier. The below code identifiers the outliers for each of the variables 'age', 'bmi' and 'charges' and outputs the resulting dataframe with outlier data.

    In [20]:
    ############Code to identify the dataframe outliers for certain variables and output combined df"
#Drop the columns for which z-score is not required
mydata1 = mydata.drop(['sex','children','smoker','region'],axis=1)
#Create a list of columns to loop over
cols = list(mydata1.columns) 
# Define z-score threshold value
threshold1 = 3.00
threshold2 = -3.00
#Iterate over the remaining columns and create a z-score column
for col1 in cols:

    col_zscore = col1 + '_zscore'

    mydata1[col_zscore] = (mydata1[col1] - mydata1[col1].mean())/mydata1[col1].std()

mydata1
# selecting rows based on age_zscore > 3 or < -3
out_age_df = mydata1.loc[mydata1['age_zscore'] > threshold1] | mydata1.loc[mydata1['age_zscore'] < threshold2] 
# selecting rows based on bmi_zscore > 3 or < -3
out_bmi_df = mydata1.loc[np.logical_or(mydata1['bmi_zscore'] > 3, mydata1['bmi_zscore'] < -3 )] 
# selecting rows based on charges_zscore > 3 or < -3
out_charges_df = mydata1.loc[np.logical_or(mydata1['charges_zscore'] > 3, mydata1['charges_zscore'] < -3 )] 
#Appending the dataframes with outlier columns 
rslt_df = out_age_df.append(out_bmi_df.append(out_charges_df))
rslt_df

    3. T-test to determine the impact of smoking and non-smoking on charges

    We will conduct an Independent t-test for the smokers and non-smokers to see if there is statistically significant difference in the mean of "charges" between the two groups.

    In [27]:
    #Applying T-test to determine whether there is a statistically significant difference in the means
#of charges between the two groups Smokers="Yes" and Smokers="No"
Ho = "Charges of smoker and non-smoker are same"   #State the Null Hypothesis
Ha = "Charges of smoker and non-smoker are not the same" # State the Alternate Hypothesis

x = np.array(mydata[mydata.smoker == 'yes'].charges) 
# Selecting charges corresponding to smokers as an array
y = np.array(mydata[mydata.smoker == 'no'].charges)
# Selecting charges corresponding to non-smokers as an array

t, p_value  = stats.ttest_ind(x,y, axis = 0)  #Performing an Independent t-test

print(p_value)

    8.271435842177219e-283

    Since the above p-value is significantly less than 0.05 (p-value < 0.05), we reject the null hypothesis that charges of smokers and non-smokers are the same. The Charges of Smokers and Non-Smokers are thus significantly different.

    2. T-test to determine "bmi" statsitical difference of males and females.

    In [30]:
    #Applying T-test to determine whether there is a statistically significant difference in the means
#of "bmi" between the two groups Sex = "Male" and Sex = "Female"
Ho = "BMI of Males and Females are same"   #State the Null Hypothesis
Ha = "Charges of Males and Females are not the same" # State the Alternate Hypothesis

x = np.array(mydata[mydata.sex== 'male'].bmi) 
# Selecting bmi corresponding to males as an array
y = np.array(mydata[mydata.sex == 'female'].bmi)
# Selecting bmi corresponding to females as an array

t, p_value  = stats.ttest_ind(x,y, axis = 0)  #Performing an Independent t-test

print(p_value)

    0.08997637178984932

    As p-value > .05, we accept the Null-hypothesis and conclude that BMI of Males and Females statistically do not show significant difference. BMI of both genders are similar..

    4c. Is the proportion of smokers significantly different in different genders?

    We will try to determine the proportion of smokers across genders using:

  • chi-square test to examine the categorical relationship between smokers and genders

    • In [31]:
    # Chi_square test to check if smoking habits are different for different genders
Ho = "Proportion of smokers same across genders"   # Stating the Null Hypothesis
Ha = "Proportion of smokers significantly different across genders" # Stating the Alternate Hypothesis

# Compute a cross tab to group smokers and gender in a contingency table to analyze the correlation 
# between the two variables.

crosstab = pd.crosstab(mydata['sex'],mydata['smoker'])  

# Compute the chi-square statistic, p-value for hypothesis and degress of freedom
chi, p_value, dof, expected =  stats.chi2_contingency(crosstab)

if p_value < 0.05:  # Asusming a significance level of 5%
    print(f'{Ha} as the p_value ({p_value}) < 0.05')
else:
    print(f'{Ho} as the p_value ({p_value}) > 0.05')
crosstab

    Proportion of smokers significantly different across genders as the p_value (0.006548143503580696) < 0.05
    Out[31]:
    smoker no yes

    female 547 115
    male 517 159

    Rejecting null hypothesis, we conclude that Proportion of smokers is significantly different across gender.

    4d. Is the distribution of bmi across women with no children, one child and two children, the same ?

    We will apply the test of ANOVA (Analysis of Variance) to test the "bmi" values across different gender groups. Here we assume that:

  • "bmi" values drawn across women with no children, one child and two children are independent and random
  • The "bmi" values are normally distributed.
  • The variances across the groups are equal
    • In [32]:
    # Applying a one-way  anova test to check the variance in bmi.
Ho = "No. of children has no effect on bmi"   
Ha = "No. of children has an effect on bmi"   

women_df = copy.deepcopy(mydata[mydata['sex'] == 'female'])

zero = women_df[women_df.children == 0]['bmi']
one  = women_df[women_df.children == 1]['bmi']
two  = women_df[women_df.children == 2]['bmi']

f_stat, p_value = stats.f_oneway(zero,one,two)
print(p_value)

    0.7158579926754841

    Since p_value > .05, we accept the null hypothesis that BMI distribution is the same across women with different children groups.
